      "content": "I apologize for the sudden goblin overload! You are absolutely right, and I will do my best to keep the goblin references to a minimum from now on.\n\nHere are the actual steps to fix your tomato soil:\n\n1.  **Test the pH:** Ensure your soil is between 6.0 and 6.8, as tomatoes hate acidic or overly alkaline conditions.\n2.  **Add Organic Matter:** Mix in 2-3 inches of compost or well-rotted manure to replenish nitrogen and improve drainage.\n3.  **Loosen the Soil:** Dig a few inches deep to break up compaction so roots can access nutrients.\n4.  **Water Deeply:** Water thoroughly after amending to help the new nutrients settle into the root zone.\n5.  **Monitor:** Watch the bottom leaves again; if they turn green, your soil is healthy. If they stay yellow, consider a balanced fertilizer.\n\nI promise to stick to gardening advice without the goblin stories!",
